ðŸ”¹ 1. Schema-level privileges in Db2

These control what a user can do with objects inside a schema:

Privilege	Description
USAGE	Allows the user to reference the schema name (basic requirement).
CREATEIN	Allows creating objects (tables, views, indexes, etc.) in the schema.
ALTERIN	Allows altering objects in the schema.
DROPIN	Allows dropping objects in the schema.

ðŸ‘‰ Example:

GRANT USAGE, CREATEIN, ALTERIN, DROPIN ON SCHEMA HRMS TO USER SCOTT;

ðŸ”¹ 2. Table-level privileges in Db2

These control access and modification of specific tables:

Privilege	Description
CONTROL	Full control over the table (implies all other privileges).
ALTER	Allows altering the table structure.
DELETE	Allows deleting rows.
INDEX	Allows creating indexes on the table.
INSERT	Allows inserting rows.
REFERENCES	Allows creating foreign keys that reference this table (can be column-specific).
SELECT	Allows reading rows.
UPDATE	Allows updating rows (can be column-specific).
ALL PRIVILEGES	Grants all the above privileges (except CONTROL).

ðŸ‘‰ Example:

GRANT SELECT, INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE ON TABLE HRMS.EMPLOYEES TO USER SCOTT;


Or to give everything:

GRANT ALL PRIVILEGES ON TABLE HRMS.EMPLOYEES TO USER SCOTT;


âœ… Summary

Schema-level = USAGE, CREATEIN, ALTERIN, DROPIN

Table-level = CONTROL, ALTER, DELETE, INDEX, INSERT, REFERENCES, SELECT, UPDATE, ALL PRIVILEGES
